<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Warns of Global AIDS Catastrophe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The AIDS pandemic, if not
curbed, would cause a "catastrophe of an unimaginable scale" and
bring economies to a standstill, the World Bank said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"As much as we focus on Africa, which is the global epicenter
of the epidemic, we are equally concerned about the growing
epidemics in Asia and eastern Europe, as well as in Latin America -
-especially the Caribbean," the World Bank said in a paper
presented to the 13th International AIDS Conference in Durban,
South Africa, which ended on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"These regions have been spared the worst so far, but could
easily see the epidemic repeat what it has done and continues to
do in Africa," the bank said, noting that "given the large
population of Asia, that would represent catastrophe of an
unimaginable scale."
</P>
<P>
The United Nations estimated that out of a total of 34.3
million AIDS sufferers across the world, east Asia and the Pacific
region (excluding Australia and New Zealand) has 530,000 while
south and southeast Asia has 5.6 million.
</P>
<P>
"Throughout Africa, the epidemic has literally put the future
at stake," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
UNAIDS estimated that there are 24.5 million AIDS sufferers in
sub-Saharan Africa and the World Bank has set aside 500 million U.
S. dollars for AIDS programs in the region.
</P>
<P>
"AIDS already represents the foremost threat to development in
Africa, and an ominous threat in much of the rest of the
developing world. Until the world has credibly addressed the
epidemic, we cannot regard anything else we do in development as
secure," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
It said that AIDS is hitting labor forces in public and private
sectors, eroding productivity, raising the cost of doing business,
deterring investment, depleting an already scarce supply of
qualified managers and policy-makers, making a "severe impact" on
health and education and depriving the poor of chances to improve
their lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
