<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Seals off Pipeline Fire Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has barred
any entry into the scene of Monday's oil pipeline fire at Adeje
village near the town of Warri in Nigeria's oil-rich Niger Delta
region, media here reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The decision, according to Environment Minister of State Ime
Okopido, was taken to avert another explosion because the air was
still pregnant with petrol fumes.
</P>
<P>
Okopido, who led a Federal Government team to the scene on
Thursday, directed security agencies in the state, the Pipelines
and Products Marketing Company and the local government to provide
an indefinite round-the-clock security in the area.
</P>
<P>
Defaulters of the order should be apprehended, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Governor James Ibori urged those wounded to come out
of hiding as the state government was providing free medical
treatment for the fire victims.
</P>
<P>
The explosion happened on Monday when people were using buckets
to collect petrol flowing from the pipeline after it had been
punctured by thieves on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
About 300 people have been confirmed dead in the accident.
</P>
</TEXT>
