<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rebels Keep Battling Government Troops in North Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Liberian rebels were still fighting
the government forces on Friday in the northern part of the
country, said Liberian Defense Minister Daniel Chea in the capital
Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
Chea accused the rebels, who he said numbered around 500, of
rampaging through villages in Lofa county on the Guinea-Liberian
border since they launched the cross-border attack on July 8,
reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Liberian President Charles Taylor had earlier denied that the
government forces had lost control of any towns, saying only "a
few individuals" had been lost.
</P>
<P>
"We have enough people in the Lofa area to deal with the
situation," Chea said, adding that the Liberian troops "have
managed to contain them (rebels) in the Voinjama corridor" near
Lofa county.
</P>
<P>
Chea expressed concern at the instability of Liberia's borders
with Guinea and Sierra Leone, which are all but impossible to
police because of the terrain.
</P>
<P>
Dissidents opposed to the Liberian president attacked twice in
the border area during 1999, causing a diplomatic standoff
between Liberia and Guinea.
</P>
<P>
Guinean President Lansana Conte has rejected suggestions that
his administration was in some way linked to the attack.
</P>
<P>
Chea called for support from both Guinea and Sierra Leone and
from the 16-strong Economic Community of West African States.
</P>
<P>
According to the Liberian government, the current incursion was
being led by fighters loyal to faction leaders from the civil war,
Alhaji Kromah and Roosevelt Johnson, both now in exile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
