<DOCNO> XIE20000716.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Right-Wing Demonstrators Rally against Barak EDS-2nd lead-writethru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEL AVIV, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of thousands of Israeli
right-wing demonstrators rallied Sunday evening at Rabin Square in
the center of Tel Aviv to protest against the ongoing Camp David
summit negotiating for an end to the half-century Arab-Israeli
conflict.
</P>
<P>
Organized by various settler's organizations and the opposition
Likud Party, the protestors also expressed opposition to the
government's intentions to withdraw from large areas of the
territories and dismantle some Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
"The peace that Prime Minister Ehud Barak is seeking is unjust
and that peace is not the peace we wanted," Likud Party leader
Ariel Sharon told the rally.
</P>
<P>
He accused Barak for conducting a dangerous peace talks at the
summit.
</P>
<P>
Sharon also called on all the participants and other Israelis to
join him to fight for personal and national interests.
</P>
<P>
The organizers hired more than 1,000 buses to transport the
protestors from all over Israel to the rally and expected over 100,
000 people to show up. But participants are in fact fewer than
expected.
</P>
<P>
Four Israeli buses were attacked by the Palestinians earlier
Sunday in the village of Kalandia, south of the West Bank city of
Ramallah, after the drivers who tried to arrive at Beit El
settlement to pick up settlers for the rally made a wrong turn.
</P>
<P>
The stunned drivers managed to make an escape, after their buses
were attacked by angry Palestinians equipped with sticks, clubs and
rocks. Three of the buses were burnt completely while another one
was semi-burnt, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
The four drivers were evicted to Hadassah Hospital in Jerusalem.
They were not injured, but suffered from shock and anxiety, doctors
said.
</P>
<P>
At the rally, a middle-aged male settler from the West Bank, who
asked not to named, told Xinhua that he strongly opposes the
government's intention to transfer more territories to the
Palestinians, including the settlement where he lives.
</P>
<P>
"I do not care what kind of peace agreement Barak is to sign
with the Palestinians, but I will not move my family from the
settlement," the settler, who has five children, added.
</P>
<P>
A 13-year-old boy from Haifa, a coastal city in northern Israel,
said that he will not agree to give up more land to the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Scheduled speakers at the rally also included representatives of
the settlements in the Golan Heights, the Jordan Valley and the
West Bank, Yisrael Ba'aliya leader Natan Sharansky, National
Religious Party leader Yitzhak Levy.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli right-wing political parties and settler's
organizations strongly oppose Barak's possible territorial
concessions to the Palestinians at the summit, which was called by
U.S. President Bill Clinton and also attended by Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The summit, which started at the Camp David near Washington on
Tuesday, is aimed at solving the key issues such as Jerusalem,
borders, refugees, settlements and water, and reaching a framework
agreement on all these issues ahead of a September 13 deadline for
a final peace accord.
</P>
<P>
The organizers proclaimed that the rally would be "the mother of
all demonstrations" against the summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
