<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-Palestinian Deals Near: Israeli Website </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Despite conflicting media
reports, Israeli and Palestinian negotiators at Camp David in the
United States are close to reaching a peace agreement, Israel's
leading daily Ha'aretz reported on its website Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the Palestinian delegation had
expressed optimism about the Camp David summit's outcome and had
said an agreement was near.
</P>
<P>
Nabil Amr, Palestinian National Authority's Parliament Affairs
Minister, was quoted by the report as saying that contrary to "
Israeli-spread rumors," which he claimed are intended for the
strengthening of Israeli stands, "things at Camp David are moving
along very seriously."
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian side is making efforts (for the success of the
summit) and is showing the necessary flexibility," he added.
</P>
<P>
The report also quoted an American source as saying that since
it is obvious that the pace of the negotiations are growing, he
believed that a certain degree of progress in the talks had been
made during the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The three-way summit at Camp David, attended by U.S. President
Bill Clinton, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat, had entered into its sixth day Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The talks are aimed at resolving all thorny issues between
Israel and the Palestinians, such as the fate of Jerusalem, Jewish
settlements, Palestinian refugees, borders, security and water.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. media blackout has brought many different, even
conflicting, estimates on the summit's process.
</P>
<P>
The Ha'aretz reports are contradictory to several Israeli
ministers' earlier remarks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy said Sunday afternoon that
the negotiators in the summit were far from closing their gaps.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Justice Minister Yossi Beilin also told Israel's Army
Radio that there is no room to be optimistic because there has not
been a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Minister in Prime Minister's Office Haim Ramon also
denied that Israel had made compromises regarding Israeli
sovereignty over Jerusalem, which is the most intractable and
sensitive issue in the talks.
</P>
<P>
All three ministers had phone contacts with Barak during the
weekend. However, the Ha'aretz daily is famous for its exclusive
reports. In January, it revealed a bridge peace proposal made by
the United States to Israel and Syria, which was proved afterwards
authentic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000716.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poverty Increases in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The number of poor Zambians
increased from 69.2 percent of the total population in 1996 to 72.
3 percent in 1998, according to a paper presented to the 12th
Consultative Group meeting starting here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In their joint presentation, Economics Association of Zambia
and Zambia Congress of Trade Unions said that formal employment in
the country declined to 11 percent in 1998 from 17 percent of the
labor force in 1991; in other words, only about 465,000 out of
about 4.7 million people who were able and willing to work were
actually formally employed.
</P>
<P>
This unemployment was accentuated by company closures,
liquidations, downsizing and cross-border plant re-location, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
The result has been massive brain drain involving all the
skilled grades. Others have entered the informal sector as petty
traders peddling all varieties of goods but working in an
environment that is increasingly hostile and dangerous, the paper
added.
</P>
<P>
The paper noted that a civil servant earns an average gross
monthly salary of 45 U.S. dollars but the cost of a monthly
household food basket is currently estimated at 90 dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, life expectancy has declined to 37 from
46.9 in 1990 and over 600,000 children aged 7-13 or one in every
three are not in school in the country nowadays.
</P>
<P>
Education accounts for only about 2.5 percent of the gross
domestic product, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The paper urged the government to foster human resource and
social development to sustain higher growth and reduce poverty by
increasing the quantity and quality of basic health care,
education, and other high priority services.
</P>
<P>
It also called to promote all aspects of good governance to
ensure full transparency and accountability in the management of
public resources.
</P>
<P>
Major industrial countries should open their markets to
products of Zambia, increase their assistance and consider a
cancellation of bilateral debt, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting first ever held in Zambia are attended by
representatives of the World Bank, the International Monetary Fund,
the European Union, the U.N. agencies and a number of developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is reviewing and assessing the short and long-term
economic agenda of Zambia and solicit for development assistance
to the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
