<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Forest Fires in Greece Die Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Most of the forest fires that
scorched Greece over the past weeks have died down while only two
fires remain burning Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The two fires, one in the western Peloponnese prefecture of
Achaia and the other farther to the east in Corinth prefecture,
have been partially extinguished, according to the semi-official
Athens News Agency (ANA).
</P>
<P>
More than 1,100 wildfires were reported across Greece since
the beginning of July and the government attributed the blazes to
both the high temperatures and arsons.
</P>
<P>
More than 5,000 firefighter and 6,000 soldiers, supported by
some 30 planes and more than 10 helicopters, have battled the
blazes for nearly two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Some 12,000 hectares of forest and farm lands have been
destroyed in the fires in which three people, including two Air
Force pilots died when their "Canadair" firefighting plane crashed
in central Greece Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Currently, about 26,000 soldiers are patrolling the forests
throughout the country in order to spot any new outbreaks of fire
and a dust-to-dawn curfew is still in effect for forestlands.
</P>
</TEXT>
