<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WIPO Keen on Cooperating with Egypt in Protecting IPRs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The World Intellectual Property
Organization (WIPO) is keen on cooperating with Egypt in
strengthening the country's infrastructure to protect the rights of
inventors and secure patents, WIPO chief said here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
WIPO will also embark on projects aimed at creating a new
framework for preservation of Egypt's cultural heritage and
antiquities, WIPO Director-General Kamil Idris said after meeting
with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Idris said his talks with Mubarak focused on ways of
consolidating the foundation of intellectual property rights (IPRs)
in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
WIPO is cooperating with Egypt in a program to help encourage
foreign investments in the country and expand economic development
bases. The program is also aimed at protecting Egypt's national
heritage of folklores and antiquities.
</P>
<P>
Idris, a Sudanese, arrived in Cairo last Thursday for a four-day
visit. On Sunday, he and Arab League Secretary General Esmat Abdel-
Meguid signed a memorandum of understanding between the two
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Under the memorandum, the Cairo-based pan-Arab forum and the
United Nations agency based in Geneva will exchange information on
intellectual property rights and cooperate in drawing up laws in
this field in Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Idris said after the signing ceremony that the memorandum would
took activate Arab joint action in the sphere of intellectual
property rights and encourage the establishment of an Arab
financial base for the protection of intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid said the league is ready to cooperate with WIPO in
line with the vitality of the issue of intellectual property in
today's world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
