<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Peace Talks Resume to Pave Way for Final Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The new round of Burundi
peace talks resumed on Sunday with two committees, one on peace
and security and another on implementation and guarantees, in
Tanzania's northern town of Arusha to discuss pending issues to
pave the way for a final peace accord.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the decisive peace and security committee is
expected to be attended by Jean Bosco Ndayikengurukiye, leader of
the splinter Hutu rebel group of the CNDD-FDD (the National
Council for the Defense of Democracy - Forces for the Defense of
Democracy), who had all along stayed out of the Arusha
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Another major rebel group, the PALIPEHUTU-FNL (the Hutu People'
s Liberation Party - the National Liberation Force), is also
expected to attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The peace facilitator, former South African President Nelson
Mandela, is scheduled to arrive in Arusha on Wednesday to lead the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the talks said that state leaders of Uganda,
South Africa, Burundi, Rwanda, Ethiopia, the Democratic Republic
of the Congo, Kenya, Zambia and host Tanzania have been invited to
the talks and Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim of the
Organization of African Unity will join them.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued on Sunday by the Nelson Mandela
Foundation based in Johannesburg, South Africa, a peace agreement
aimed at ending the seven-year old conflict in Burundi is expected
to be signed on August 28.
</P>
<P>
Mandela will ensure that the parties confirm their previous
pledge to endorse the comprehensive peace agreement, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
About 200,000 people, most of them civilians, have lost their
lives since the outbreak of war in the tiny central African
republic in 1993 between Hutu rebels and the army dominated by the
minority Tutsi ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks, which began in Arusha in June 1998, are
currently taking place in four committees, dealing respectively
with the nature of the Burundi conflict, democracy and good
governance, peace and security for all and economic reconstruction
and the return of refugees.
</P>
<P>
However, peace negotiators still remain divided on a number of
crucial points, notably the arrangement for a cease-fire;
restructuring of the Tutsi-dominated army, including integration
of Hutu rebels; whether or not foreign peacekeepers will be needed;
amnesty for certain crimes of the past; and who will lead the
transition government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
