<HEADLINE> Khatami's Visit a New Chapter in Ties with Germany: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi said here Sunday that President Mohammad Khatami's visit
to Germany on July 10-12 has opened a new chapter in Tehran-Berlin
relations. Kharrazi told the state-run IRNA news agency
that the door is now open for any kind of cooperation between Iran
and Germany in economic, political and cultural fields.
</P>
<P>
Despite anti-Iran elements' opposition to the visit, German
statesmen, party leaders and outstanding personalities welcomed it
and made extensive arrangements for a positive atmosphere, Kharrazi
said, adding that all this indicated German government's firm will
to improve relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister pointed out that joint-venture projects,
cooperation in third countries, international cooperation in the
fields of disarmament, anti-narcotics campaign, environment
protection and exchange of views on regional issues are among the
positive areas of cooperation between Iran and Germany.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed hope that expanded Tehran-Berlin relations
would have a positive impact on Iran's ties with the European
Union, as Germany is an influential member of the club.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said Germany has the potential to become Iran's largest
trading partner again after Khatami's landmark visit, the first by
an Iranian president since the 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
Germany had been Iran's largest trading partner, but it was
replaced by Italy in recent years due to strains in Tehran-Berlin
ties after a German court ruled in 1997 that Iranian government had
been involved in an assassination of exiled Iranian dissidents in
Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
