<HEADLINE> Indian Troops to Continue Peacekeeping Mission in Sierra Leone: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 16 (Xinhua) -- A day after the evacuation of
221 trapped Indian peacekeepers in Sierra Leone, Indian External
Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh on Sunday categorically ruled out
any possibility that New Delhi would pull out its troops from the
United Nations peacekeeping operations in that west African
country.
</P>
<P>
"Of course we are continuing," Singh told reporters here at a
press conference while asked whether India would have a rethink on
persisting with its troops in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The Indian peacekeepers, who had been kept in captivity for 10
weeks by Sierra Leone's Revolutionary United Front (RUF) rebels,
were evacuated on Saturday through a successful military operation
by the UN force.
</P>
<P>
"Our resolve to contribute to UN operations is not diluted in
any manner," said Singh, adding that difficult situation had been
faced in the past by Indian troops as part of UN peacekeeping
missions but this had not acted as a "deterrent."
</P>
<P>
Singh, along with India's Director General of Military
Operations Lieutenant General N C Vij, also briefed the press on
Saturday's UN evacuation mission.
</P>
<P>
Two Indian para commandos sustained shrapnel injuries and were
immediately evacuated, while the RUF rebels, who put up stiff
resistance, suffered a number of casualties, said Vij.
</P>
<P>
Indian troops seized one medium machine gun, eight light
machine guns, seven rocket launchers and one truck load of
ammunition abandoned by the RUF, he noted.
</P>
<P>
As part of the effective air operations, Indian attack
helicopters destroyed three RUF vehicles carrying their
reinforcements, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
