<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's Retail Sales Go Up in May 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's overall retail sales
in May 2000 was estimated at 2,461 million Singapore dollars (
about 1,412 million U.S. dollars), growing substantially by 21.7
percent over May 1999 and rising by 1.5 percent compared with the
2,426 million Singapore dollars (about 1,392 million U.S. dollars)
in the previous month, according to data released by Singapore
Department of Statistics (SDS) Sunday.
</P>
<P>
SDS attributed the robust year-on-year rise largely to the 62.9
percent growth in motor vehicle sales, noting excluding motor
vehicles, the overall retail sales in May 2000 increased by a
slower 3.4 percent over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Compared to April 2000, May 2000 saw the largest 14.5 percent
increase in sale of watches and jewelry, a 9.4 percent rise in
turnover of recreational goods, 3-4 percent improvement in retail
business of optical goods and books, supermarkets and
telecommunications and computers and marginally 0.1 percent growth
in sale of motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Conversely, turnover of food and beverages and furniture and
household equipment fell by 2.9 percent and 2.0 percent
respectively in May 2000 over the previous month while retailers
of wearing apparel and footwear encountered a slight decline of 0.
6 percent in their earnings in the month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the total value of catering trade in May 2000 was
estimated at 286 million Singapore dollars (about 164 million U.S.
dollars), increasing by 1.4 percent over May 1999 and by 6.1
percent over April 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
