<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan President Lures Investment from Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Rwandan President Paul
Kagame has challenged the Kenyan business community to exploit the
high economic potential of his country by investing there.
</P>
<P>
Kagame said on Saturday night that Rwanda needs outside
partners in its reconstruction efforts, according to a news
release issued by Kenya's Presidential Press Service on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has been identified as having the capacity to help in
that reconstruction, said the president.
</P>
<P>
He also assured investors of a conducive environment, noting
that his government has greatly improved security in that country
since the 1994 genocide.
</P>
<P>
It was imperative for African countries to merge in economic
blocs so as to cushion themselves against the effects of
globalization, the president noted.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda was keen on joining the East African Community, which
groups Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda currently, Kagame added.
</P>
<P>
Kagame arrived in Kenya for a two-day official visit on Friday
morning and had a lengthy meeting with Kenyan President Daniel
arap Moi on bilateral relations and regional affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
