<HEADLINE> Ethiopia, U.S. to Negotiate Open Sky Deal: Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Officials of Ethiopian and the
United States civil aviation authorities will meet at the end of
this month to negotiate on an open sky sales agreement, local
Fortune weekly reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A 12-member delegation representing the U.S. government and
aviation industry is due to arrive in Addis Ababa on July 31.
</P>
<P>
During a three-day visit, the U.S. delegation will have talks
with its Ethiopian counterpart over signing an agreement which
allows the two countries to let each other's airlines fly in their
respective territories without restrictions and limitations, the
weekly said.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian Airlines commercial flights to the United States,
which started in 1998, are still conducted on the basis of
temporary permits, the airline officials said.
</P>
<P>
According to diplomatic sources, the forthcoming U.S.
delegation would like to sign the open sky agreement with Ethiopia.
But Ethiopia's stand over the issue is not clear yet.
</P>
<P>
"The answer (to open sky agreement) is yes and no, " Daniel
Hailu, economic planning and international affairs head of the
Ethiopian Airlines, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Daniel said yes because the agreement is to make Ethiopian
Airlines keep pace with the rapidly growing liberalized aviation
industry.
</P>
<P>
He said no because the airline is concerned about jumping into
a slugfest with some of the world's heavyweight airline companies.
</P>
<P>
"We are in principle receptive of the open market sales,"
Daniel said,"but we would like to see it grow steadily and slowly.
"
</P>
<P>
He said what his airline concerns about include unfair
competition and costing sharing arrangements between partners
airlines that may disadvantage smaller airlines.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government has so far signed similar agreements with
such African countries as Ghana and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the U.S. delegation will conduct similar
negotiations with Kenyan Civil Aviation and Kenya Airways before
it comes to Ethiopia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
