<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine's Economy Shows Signs of Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine's economy has showed signs of
recovery in the first half of this year, with the gross domestic
product (GDP) and the gross industrial output value jumping 5
percent and 10.8 percent respectively from the year-ago levels,
the latest figures released by the Statistics Office show.
</P>
<P>
During the period, direct foreign investment and domestic
investment in the country's infrastructure rose by 50 percent and
21 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Victor Yushchenko cited these figures as the
greatest achievements of his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine's GDP has decreased continuously since the country
declared independence from the former Soviet Union in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the country reported a 4.3 percent growth in the
gross industrial output value. However, the GDP still dropped by 0.
4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed the latest good performance to some
stimulative measures taken by the government, which include
accelerating the privatization process, a reform of the energy
sector and a new financial policy to encourage investment.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, they warned that there remain a number of
negative factors hindering the economic recovery. Among them are
an estimated inflation rate of 18.5 percent for 2000 and a present
4.29 percent unemployment rate, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
