<HEADLINE> Southeast European FMs Meet on Regional Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, July 16 (Xinhua)-- The two-day foreign ministerial
meeting of southeastern European countries ended Saturday in the
southern Macedonian resort city of Ohrid with a joint statement on
regional security and the Kosovo issue, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Noting the easing situation in the Balkan region, foreign
ministers from Albania, Bulgaria, Croatia, Greece, Bosnia, Turkey
and Macedonia agreed that there still exist issues which could
again trigger regional tension, endangering regional peace and
stability.
</P>
<P>
On the Kosovo issue, the ministers expressed their support to
the U.N. Resolution 1244 and their appreciation to all efforts
made by the international community so far.
</P>
<P>
They also criticized violence and extremist activities, calling
for more organized battle against drug, weapon and human smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Greek Foreign Minister George Papandreou said that the
cooperation among southeastern European countries would play a
major role in implementing the Stability Pact and in exploiting
new fields for cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
