<DOCNO> XIE20000716.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yun-7s Resume Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Six Yun-7 airplanes belonging to
Wuhan Airlines, which were pulled out of service after the June 22
plane crash,resumed service today.
</P>
<P>
They will fly on 16 routes, having passed a tight safety
inspection and extra training of crew members.
</P>
<P>
The July 22 crash killed 42 passengers and crew, and seven
people on the ground.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the plane was struck by lightning during its
descent. It then exploded in mid-air, and crashed in the suburbs
of this capital of central China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
The Yu-7 is a product of the Xi'an Airplane Industry
Corporation, and has been exported to a number of countries. It is
said to be one of the most reliable passenger airplanes in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
