<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt's Parliament Amends Electoral Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's parliament on Sunday approved
amendments to an electoral law passed in 1956 in a bid to ensure
that parliamentary elections will be monitored by members of the
judiciary.
</P>
<P>
The People's Assembly, under speaker Ahmed Fathi Sorour,
endorsed the amendments outlined in a republican decree issued by
President Hosni Mubarak last Wednesday, the country's official
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The modifications followed a July 8 ruling by the Supreme
Constitutional Court that the 1956 law was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
Under Egypt's 1971 constitution, all the polling stations for
parliamentary elections must be supervised by members of the
judiciary. But the 1956 law allowed civil servants to oversee
smaller booths while demanding the principal stations be monitored
by members of the judiciary. The country's opposition parties have
long been charging that the government had relentlessly rigged
parliamentary elections and calling for changes.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak called last Wednesday for emergency meetings of the
People's Assembly and the Shura (Consultative) Council to amend the
1956 law for members of the judiciary to exercise full supervision
of parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
The Shura Council, which has no legislative powers, endorsed the
amendments on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is expected to hold parliamentary elections in November.
Minister of State for Parliamentary Affairs Kamal El-Shazli has
said that Egypt has less than 10,000 members of the judiciary, and
the polling stations will amount to 42,000.
</P>
<P>
The country's last parliamentary elections were in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
