<HEADLINE> Israel's Military Officials Voice Concern over Iran's Missile Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli defense establishment
has reacted with concern to Iran's successful test-firing of an
upgraded version of its medium-range Shahab-3 missile on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio Sunday quoted Israeli Defense Force (IDF) Chief of
Staff Shaul Mofaz as saying the Iranians are also making great
efforts to acquire non-conventional weapon technology.
</P>
<P>
This, together with the Shahab missiles, threatens not just
Israel but all the countries that are within the 1,300-kilometer
radius range of Iran, Mofaz said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Shahab missile, Defense Ministry Director-
general Amos Yaron said there is a distance between Iran's ability
to develop the missile and actually using it against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh said Iran is
seeking to gain hegemony in the Moslem world and it perceives
itself as guardian of Islamic rights.
</P>
<P>
This becomes evident not only in the development of its weapons
capability but in its desire to continue controlling terrorism,
Sneh told Israel Radio on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The radio report also quoted a reserve brigadier as denying
Iran's missle program is first and foremost targeted at Israel but
rather Iran's neighbors. The officer said Iran will threaten
several of its neighbors including Iraq, Pakistan, Afghanistan and
Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Israel is preparing an answer to the Iranian Shahab-3 missile,
the officer noted.
</P>
<P>
Israel believes Iran will have a small number of nuclear
warheads which will be operational in about five years, he added.
The launching of the missile Saturday was not seen as a surprise to
Israel which has been following its development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
