<HEADLINE> Death Toll Rises to 186 in Manila Dumpsite Landslide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The death toll in a garbage
dumpsite landslide in Metro Manila has climbed to 186 as rescuers
retrieved more bodies of victims from tons of trash Sunday,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
As of 15:45 p.m. Sunday, search and rescue workers have
recovered 186 bodies at the dumpsite at Payatas in Quezon City,
Metro Manila, the National Disaster Coordination Council said in a
latest report.
</P>
<P>
A total of 602 families or 2,895 persons have been evacuated to
safe grounds, it added.
</P>
<P>
The landslide, set off last Monday by heavy rains from recent
typhoons, submerged more than 100 shanties at the foot of a 15-
meter-high mountain of trash.
</P>
<P>
The council said it could still not determine the number of
people missing after the landslide. Local officials and rescuers
believe some 200 people might still be buried in the heap of
garbage.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado, who heads the council, said
Saturday in a TV program that search and rescue operations will
indefinitely continue until the last body is retrieved.
</P>
<P>
There were reportedly 50,000 people residing in Payatas. The
open dumpsite was scheduled to be closed in 1999, but the closure
was held back for lack of an alternative disposal site for Quezon
City's more than 700 tons of daily garbage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
