<HEADLINE> AIDS Ballooning in India: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The AIDS (Acquired Immuno-
Deficiency Syndrome) disease is continuously spreading in India
with as many as 3.5 million people across the south Asian country
already contracting the disease, a recent report by the United
Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) said.
</P>
<P>
"There is evidence of the continued spread of HIV (Human
Immunodeficiency Virus) both within high-risk groups and,
importantly, to the general population," the Press Trust of India
(PTI) quoted the UNICEF report as saying here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The southwestern coastal state of Maharashtra is heading the
country in the number of AIDS and HIV positive patients, followed
by the state of Manipur in the northeast, said the report, adding
that in both states over one percent of the local population is
infected.
</P>
<P>
The report cautioned India, which has the highest number of
people with HIV/AIDS in the world, against it becoming an epidemic,
the PTI noted.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, "heterosexual intercourse" is the main
mode of HIV/AIDS transmission in India, while in some northeastern
states intravenous drug injection users have constituted the
majority of the patients.
</P>
<P>
The last four years have witnessed a broadening of the epidemic
across the southern and western states, such as Andhra Pradesh and
Tamil Nadu, and the impact of the epidemic is already felt in
cities like Mumbai and Imphal, capitals of Maharashtra and Manipur,
where bed-occupancy rates for HIV-related illnesses of between 20
and 40 percent are reported, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
