here on Saturday to assess the prospects for peace in Sri Lanka's
long-running civil war which has plagued the country since 1983.
</P>
<P>
Their arrival follows the departure of Peter Westamacott, under
secretary of state in the Foreign and Commonwealth Office of
Britain, who held talks with senior members of the government and
opposition on Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
The increased number of overseas visitors coincides with
efforts by Sri Lankan President Chandrika Kumaratunga to end the
Sri Lankan civil war. She is talking with minority Tamil parties
in a bid to hammer out a consensus on constitutional reform
proposals which will give more autonomy to regions, including the
north and east, where the LTTE rebels are fighting for an
independent homeland.
</P>
<P>
The government and the main opposition United National Party
reached consensus on the constitutional reform proposals early
this month after four months of peace talks. Kumaratunga said she
would present the proposals before Parliament in early August.
</P>
