<HEADLINE> World Forum to Focus on Diamond-Turned War Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANTWERP, Belgium, July 16 (Xinhua) -- World diamond traders are
scheduled to start on Monday discussing revenues from diamond
sales that were used to fund civil wars in Africa.
</P>
<P>
An international outcry over the use of illegal diamond
revenues to fund wars in Africa where lots of people have been
killed will be the limelight at this year's world diamond
conference to be held here at the world's largest diamond trading
center.
</P>
<P>
The biannual event happened to follow a United Nations embargo
over Sierra Leone diamonds in an attempt to cut off funding for
the African country's Revolutionary United Front.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. embargo on the export of Sierra Leone diamonds has
raised a call for global measures to stop the smuggling of
diamonds from one African country to another in order to
circumvent national laws and international sanctions.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. report published in March on sanctions against illegal
Angolan diamonds used to fund the UNITA criticized some companies
in the diamond industry for allegedly allowing trade in what has
been described as conflict diamonds to flourish.
</P>
<P>
But observers believed that it would not be easy in that the
complicated chain system of dealers will only make diamond trade
difficult to track and therefore difficult to halt trade of
conflict diamonds.
</P>
<P>
The Antwerp conference draws representatives from around the
world's diamond-producing countries, mining companies and diamond-
cutting centers. Apart from diamond-producing countries in Africa,
Russia and Canada will also be present while such diamond-cutting
centers as India, Belgium, Thailand, Israel and the United States
will also be attending the conference.
</P>
<P>
The global diamond business produces 6.8 billion U.S. dollars
in diamonds which in turn generate a retail diamond jewelry sales
of around 56 billion dollars each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
