<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Students Go on Fast to Protest Court Verdict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Iranian students on Sunday staged
a "political fast" before the office building of the Majlis
(parliament) to protest the court verdict on last year's student
dormitory case and the imprisonment of a reformist lawyer.
</P>
<P>
The fast, held by Iran's most influential student organization,
the Office to Foster Unity (OFU), may continue in the next few days
to urge the Majlis to take quick measures to overhaul the
conservative judiciary, said a statement released by OFU.
</P>
<P>
A military court here on Tuesday acquitted former Tehran police
commander Farhad Nazari along with 17 other co-accused policemen
who stood trial for forcibly entering a Tehran University dormitory
on July 8 last year to crack down on student protests against the
closure of the outspoken Persian daily Salam.
</P>
<P>
Nazari was tried on several charges, including illegally
entering the dormitory complex, ignoring an order of the Interior
Ministry not to use tear gas to suppress students and damage to
university property.
</P>
<P>
Many students were beaten and at least one was killed in the
police raid, which led to the worst nation-wide unrest Iran had
experienced since the aftermath of the 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
Ironically, only two minor defendants in the case got prison
terms according to Tuesday's verdict, one was sentenced to two
years in jail for breach of order and the other to 91 days in jail
plus a small fine for stealing an electric razor in the student
dormitory.
</P>
<P>
The verdict invited protests from many reformist organizations,
including the most influential Islamic Iran Participation Front.
Reformers believe that the trial and verdict are mostly symbolic
because those responsible for the incident remain unpunished.
</P>
<P>
Before the verdict was issued, the conservative judiciary had
issued arrest warrant for Mohsen Rahami, a reformist cleric lawyer,
for allegedly making and distributing video cassettes, the contents
of which are said to have insulted some officials.
</P>
<P>
Rahami, a law professor, was the lawyer for the student
plaintiffs in the university dormitory case. He also defended
various reformist clients in a number of high-profile cases.
</P>
<P>
Rahami and Ms. Shirin Ebadi, also a reformist lawyer, went on
trial Saturday at a Terhan court.
</P>
<P>
Akbar Atri, one of the leaders of the OFU, said on Sunday that
the political fast launched by the students before the Majlis is in
conformity with the Constitution, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that the students made the decision due to the weakness
of the judiciary in performing its functions. "The judiciary has
disappointed us because it failed to have our rights restored," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Atri pointed out that another aim of the student movement is to
show its support for the reformist-controlled Majlis, which only
started work in May but has to overcome conservative pressures to
carry out its reformist tasks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
