<HEADLINE> Barak, Lapid Discuss Camp David Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
and head of the opposition Shinui party Yosef Lapid discussed on
Sunday the ongoing three-way Camp David summit.
</P>
<P>
Lapid told Israel Radio that Barak has called him Sunday morning
from Camp David and gave him a summary of the situation at the
talks with Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
"Barak has asked specifically not to talk publicly about the
conversation in the face of a virtual news blackout," Lapid said.
</P>
<P>
"The only thing that I can tell you is that he doesn't sound
like the most optimistic person in the world," lapid added.
</P>
<P>
Asked if this meant Barak would fail to forge the planned
framework agreement for a final peace, Lapid said: "I didn't say he
is not coming back with agreement and I didn't prophesy in this
direction or the other, and I don't want to enter into this."
</P>
<P>
Shinui, or Religious Reformation Party, has six members of the
120-member Knesset (parliament) and the party would be asked to
join a new coalition that Barak will form on his return from the
summit, which was also attended by U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The summit, which started on Monday at Camp David near
Washington, is aimed at solving the key issues such as Jerusalem,
border, refugees, settlement and water and reaching a framework
agreement on these issues ahead of the target September deadline
for a final peace deal.
</P>
<P>
After days of "soft negotiations" and hours of restating old
positions, the Israeli and Palestinian teams at the summit got down
to real work over the weekend, splitting into working groups and
dealing with a verbal U.S. bridging proposal.
</P>
<P>
Officials on all sides admitted that the talks were tense and
little progress has been made. Tensions between Israeli and
Palestinian negotiators heated up over the weekend as the sides
delved deeper into the core of the key issues.
</P>
<P>
Arafat threatened to walk out of the summit after receiving a U.
S.
bridging proposal with a map that was too similar to the Israeli
position. 
</P>
</TEXT>
