<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Chinese Asked to Lend Helping Hand to Aboriginals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad Sunday urged the Chinese community in the country
to lend a helping hand to rebuild Bumiputera (aboriginals)
businesses affected by the recent economic turmoil in efforts to
accelerate national prosperity.
</P>
<P>
He said that during the recession, many Bumiputera companies
collapsed because they were too new and were almost completely
destroyed by the currency attack.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that when the new economic policy was first
launched (in the early 1970s) for the indigenous people to have a
share in the economic wealth, the Chinese had cooperated in such a
way that it was successfully implemented.
</P>
<P>
Their Bumiputera counterparts however must understand that they
must work very hard and practice prudent financial management and
cannot blame the Chinese community if they fail, he said when
opening a Chinese Chamber building in Kuching, Sarawak, East
Malaysia, Bernama news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that the government recognized the contribution
of the Chinese community in the country's emergence as one of the
strongest economies in the developing countries due to their
dynamism.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese community realize the importance of reducing the
disparity in the economic wealth among the different communities
and give them a share in it. And because they (Bumiputeras) have a
share, the feeling of jealousy and envy to the Chinese community
have almost disappeared," Mahathir was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
This was the reason why during the economic turmoil there was
no outbreak of racial fighting in the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said when the Bumiputeras are enriched, a market is
being created for the Chinese to produce goods to sell to them.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir lauded the Chinese community which comprises the
second largest ethnic group in Sarawak for building up much of the
state's economic wealth.
</P>
<P>
He said Sarawak had remained a peaceful place because the
Chinese understood the cultural values of the indigenous people by
getting along well with them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
