<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The technical committee of the United Arab Emirates
Contractors' Association is drawing schemes to classify the UAE's
estimated 1,400 contractors, according to the association's General
Manager Rashed Ahmed Rashed.
</P>
<P>
Rashed said the classification is expected to be completed by
the end of this year, according to a report in the July issue of "
Contractors' News".
</P>
<P>
The report also said the classification will rationalize bidding
procedures and level the playing field among the contractors.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Oman has secured a loan from a consortium of
international banks to finance two natural gas pipeline projects
expected to cost a total of 306 million U.S. dollars, according to
Sunday's Dubai-based daily "Gulf News".
</P>
<P>
"We have already secured the loan for the pipeline projects from
a consortium led by industrial Bank of Japan 8302.T, which also
includes Bank National de Paris and the Arab Banking Cooperation,"
the newspaper quoted a senior project official as saying.
</P>
<P>
He declined to give the exact value of the loan, but said it
would finance most of the projects.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Elf Petroleum Qatar and the National Petroleum
Construction Co. (NPCC) of Abu Dhabi have signed a multi-million
dollar contract on Saturday, according to Sunday's Dubai-based
daily "Gulf News"
</P>
<P>
The deal was signed for engineering, procurement, installation
and commissioning (EPIC) of the second phase for the expansion of
crude oil production facilities at the offshore Al Khalij Block 6
field.
</P>
<P>
The contract covers the design engineering, procurement,
installation and commissioning of three platforms, about 50
kilometers of 10 inch, 16 inch and 20 inch diameter pipelines,
linking the platforms to the processing and loading terminal, sub-
sea power cable and some modification works to existing facilities.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The world's leading IT company Microsoft granted
100, 000 U.S dollars to Emirate Internet society in Dubai on
Saturday according to a partnership agreement aimed at spreading
the use of Internet in the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is considered the first of its kind in the region
which embodies a new step that contributes in enhancing the new
economy and the use of Internet in the current educational system.
</P>
