<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: EPZs Develop Rapidly in Bangladesh By Chen Jian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- With a view to accelerating the pace
of industrial development and generating productive employment
opportunities, Bangladesh has taken different measures to promote
the development of export processing zones (EPZ), the newest of
which is the Comilla EPZ inaugurated Saturday in southeastern
district Comilla.
</P>
<P>
Comilla EPZ, the fourth EPZ in the country, is to be built on
258 acres adjacent to Comilla Airport, in which 208 industrial
plots will be set up.
</P>
<P>
The development works for infrastructure began in April last
year,with an estimated cost of 835.6 million taka (16 million U.S.
dollars), and the first-phase works are expected to be completed
in 2001.
</P>
<P>
The authorities hoped the Comilla EPZ would attract foreign
investment of 3.6 billion taka (69.2 million dollars) and create
jobs for over 40,000 people when operations go in full swing.
</P>
<P>
While laying the foundation of the much-awaited Comilla EPZ,
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina said it would usher in economic
development and prosperity not only for the district, but also for
the country as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Aiming at promoting economic progress, the decision to set up
EPZ in the country was taken by the government in 1978. Two years
later,an act was passed in the parliament, which was known as
Bangladesh Export Processing Zones Authority Act 1980.
</P>
<P>
Initially Chittagong EPZ, the first EPZ in the country, started
its operation in 1983. Later in 1993, another EPZ was set up in
the capital city Dhaka. Investors from 18 different countries of
the world including South Korea, Japan, Italy, Britain and the
United States have so far invested in Chittagong and Dhaka EPZs.
</P>
<P>
Investment in Chittagong EPZ has reached 283 million dollars
while that in Dhaka EPZ has come up to 144 million dollars as of
June 30, 2000. The investment in both EPZs has increased by 22
percent on an average during last four years.
</P>
<P>
The export from the zones is also very encouraging, with goods
worth 891 million dollars being exported from the existing two
EPZs in the last fiscal year 1999-2000, which accounted for 15
percent of the total national export. The average growth rate of
export of the two EPZs stands at 37 percent during last four years.
</P>
<P>
With the successful operation of Chittagong and Dhaka EPZs, the
present government decided to set up some more EPZs in other parts
of the country. Accordingly foundation stone of Mongla EPZ was
laid in 1998 in the southwestern port city. The construction work
of Mongla EPZ is going on in full swing, which is expected to be
finished by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The government has also decided to set up another two EPZs in
northern districts of Pabna and Nilphamari in the next one or two
years for balanced regional development of the country.
</P>
<P>
The speedy development of EPZs will undoubtedly attract more
foreign investment with the favorable policies, comparatively good
infrastructure and facilities, easy communication and cheap labors,
accordingly accelerate the country's transition to export-oriented
economy and promote the overall development of the country,
however,to set up too many EPZs in a rather short period will
inevitably bring about lots of problems, experts here said.
</P>
<P>
In the first place, to set up too many EPZs at the same time
may cause shortage of fund, which will result in the lagging
construction of infrastruture.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the imperfect related rules and regulations in the
EPZs and the wide-spread red-tapism in the governmental sectors
may hit the investors' confidence.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, the hasty setting-up of EPZs may lead to vicious
competition among the EPZs for foreign investment, which is
harmful to the national interest.
</P>
<P>
Noting the importance of the EPZs for the development of the
country, Experts urged the government to take necessary measures
to tackle these problems and make sure the exuberant EPZs won't
become some white elephants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
