<HEADLINE> Tibet to Turn Tibetan Medicine into Pillar Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Traditional Tibetan medicine will
play an increasingly important role in promoting and safeguarding
the health of human beings today, according to a senior official
from the Tibet autonomous Regional government.
</P>
<P>
The regional government has listed the development of Tibetan
medicine as a key project for attracting both domestic and foreign
investment, said Legqog, chairman of the regional government.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at the on-going three-day international
symposium on Tibetan medicine, which opened here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that neighboring Qinghai Province has also listed
the sector as a key industry for local economic development.
</P>
<P>
Tibetan medicine is a unique medicine system developed by the
Tibetan people over the past thousands of years by absorbing the
advantages of traditional Chinese medicine, ancient Indian
medicine and ancient Arabian medicine. It is proved to be
especially effective in treating diseases of digestive and
cardiovascular systems as well as immune diseases.
</P>
<P>
To boost the production of Tibetan medicines, which had been
hand-made for thousands of years, the state has invested 200
million yuan (24 million U.S. dollars) to build modern Tibetan
medicine plants in Tibet and Qinghai.
</P>
<P>
The Tibetan Medicine Plant in Tibet, China's largest,
manufactures more than 60 million capsules, more than 30 million
granules, and over 100,000 tons of traditional Tibetan medicines
annually.
</P>
<P>
At present, more than a dozen kinds of Tibetan medicines have
been included in the Chinese Pharmacopoeia, 336 kinds are produced
according to the country's ministerial standards, and two kinds of
newly-developed Tibetan medicines have been exported to the United
States, Japan, the Republic of Korea and other countries.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau boasts more than
2,000 kinds of plants, 159 kinds of animals and over 80 kinds of
minerals that are suitable for making Tibetan medicines.
</P>
<P>
The rich resources, together with rapid developing high
technologies, provide a firm foundation for turning Tibetan
medicine into a pillar of the local economy, said Legqog.
</P>
<P>
The central government's strategy to develop the vast western
region will also give a boost to the local effort, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
