</P>
<P>
-- Iran said Saturday it had successfully test-fired an upgraded
version of its medium-range Shahab-3 missile, amid concern in
Israel and the United States. The Ballistic missile has a range of
1,300 Kilometers, making it capable of striking Israel.
</P>
<P>
In response, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said:"The
Strength of the IDF (Israel Defense Forces) and the strengthening
of Israel by peace agreements are together our answer to the
launch."
</P>
<P>
Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh said the successful test
run is a worrying sign. Former defense minister Moshe Arens said
this was the missile's first successful test run, and it will take
time until it becomes fully operational. Meanwhile, Iran continues
to work on the Shahab-4, with a long-range capability of 2,000 km.
