<HEADLINE> China to Build Big Reservoir in Northeast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, July 16 (Xinhua) -- China is to build a large reservoir
in its northeast province of Heilongjiang to prevent future floods.
</P>
<P>
The State Council has already approved the project, which will
need an investment of 4.5 billion yuan (560 million U.S. dollars),
government sources say.
</P>
<P>
The Ni'erji reservoir will be built on the upper reaches of the
Nenjiang River and is expected to hold 8.1 billion cubic meters of
water, one-fifth that of the reservoir in the Three Gorges.
</P>
<P>
Devastating floods on the Nenjiang River and nearby Songhua
River in 1998 affected millions of people and caused tens of
billion yuan in economic losses in the northeastern region, China'
s major granary and industrial basis.
</P>
<P>
The new reservoir will provide a shield for big oil fields and
key transportation lines, said the sources, adding that it will
also generate 550 million kwh of electricity annually.
</P>
<P>
It is also expected to ease the shortage of water in part of
the region and improve irrigation and shipping. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000716.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Lumberjacks Become Tree Planters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Vegetation at the upper reaches
of the Yangtze River, the longest in China, has increased since
China banned the logging primitive forests there in 1998 following
the devastating floods downstream.
</P>
<P>
By now, more than 200,000 lumberjacks in the area have put down
their saws and axes and joined the army of tree planters. And the
government has earmarked more than two billion yuan (about 240
million U.S. dollars) for planting trees and protecting forests
there.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in the past two years, 306,700 hectares of
trees have been planted and 9.3 million hectares of natural
forests have been put under good protection.
</P>
<P>
Excessive logging in the past several decades has resulted in
degradation of the ecological environment at the upper reaches of
the Yangtze. In the 1980s, serious soil erosion expanded to an
area of 350,000 square kilometers, with about 1.6 billion tons of
mud and sand washed into the river each year.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze River valley is China's most important economic
center, covering one-fifth of the country's territory, a quarter
of its cultivated land, and one-third of its population. Combined
industrial and agricultural output value of the area accounts for
two-fifths of the country's total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000716.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bangladeshi Police Hunt for Killers  By Pan Xiaozhu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Seventy nine people have been
arrested in a combing operation launched by Bangladeshi law-
enforcing agencies on Saturday for their alleged involvement in
the massacre in Chittagong on July 12, in which nine people were
gunned down by members of Islami Chhatra Shibir (Islami Student
Front).
</P>
<P>
The operation was launched jointly by Chittagong metropolitan
and district police aided by Bangladesh Rifles and armed battalion
police.
</P>
<P>
After getting the directive of Home Minister Mohammed Nasim,
different law-enforcing agencies had stated non-stop combing
operations at least in seven districts in the country including
Chittagong, 264 kilometers southeast of Dhaka, Chittagong Hill
Tracts and Rajshahi, 272 kilometers west of Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
Police force in Chittagong made raid at different places in the
sea port and other areas adjacent to the city with a list of 2000
hard-core and identified terrorists.
</P>
<P>
At least 38 activists and leaders of the Islami Chhatra Shibir,
the student wing of Jammat-e-Islami, were arrested in separate
raids on eight residential halls of the Rajshahi University.
</P>
<P>
A tense situation is reportedly prevailing on the campus
following the police raid. Panic-stricken students have left their
hall rooms and took shelter in the houses of their relatives and
friends.
</P>
<P>
A group of armed cadres of Chhatra Shibir riding a black
microbus were alleged to have sprayed bullets on another microbus
carrying the leaders of Bangladesh Chhatra League (Bangladesh
Student League), the student wing of the ruling Awami League, on
July 12, gunning down nine people including six activists of
Chhatra League.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina Saturday called for the people to
build up resistance against the killers. Addressing a big public
meeting in Comilla, 79 kilometers southeast of the capital, she
said that the killers would have to be punished wherever found.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh Chhatra League on Thursday announced five-day
agitation program throughout the country, protesting over the
killing incident. Leaders of the league urged the government to
arrest "killer" Shibir activists immediately and demanded ban on
Jamaat-Shibir politics.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the main opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party (
BNP) demanded judicial inquiry committee to probe into the
killings in Chittagong to deal with the real culprits.
</P>
<P>
In a statement on Thursday night, BNP Secretary General Abdul
Mannan Bhuiyan expressed concern at the different activities of
the government and the ruling party and its front organizations
centering the Chittagong killings.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the reported attacks on BNP and other opposition
parties in different parts of the country in the wake of the
Chittagong killings, the BNP leader urged the ruling party to
refrain from carrying out such provocative activities.
</P>
<P>
He urged the people to remain alert against the ill motive of
spreading conflicts throughout the country centering on an
incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
