<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Launch Power-Saving Project Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is
planning to introduce special motor from next year in industrial,
commercial and domestic electrical appliances to save some 460
megawatt electricity and reduce technical system loss, load
shedding and power pilferage, the Bangladesh Observer reported
here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The special motor called Intelligent Motor Controller (IMC) is
the culmination of over 10 years' research and development in the
field of optimum motor efficiency by experts from different arenas.
</P>
<P>
The IMC to be launched as the "Power-Saving Pilot Project"
under the Ministry of Energy and Mineral Resources will be
implemented by the Power Development Board at a cost of 100
million taka (1.92 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Elaborating on the benefit of the IMC, sources said it could be
installed in different types of domestic appliances including
refrigerators, air conditioners, various types of motors in small
and medium factories and agricultural apparatuses.
</P>
<P>
It can save 35 to 40 percent power consumption from the
existing level, they added.
</P>
<P>
According to the Short Study Report on the IMC, prepared by the
Department of Project Planning of the Power Development Board, the
introduction of the IMC could save 45.33 billion taka (872 million
dollars), equivalent to the cost of 460 megawatt power entailing
generation, transmission and distribution of electricity.
</P>
<P>
It could decrease the pressure on the distribution system in
different grid lines and substations, ensuring the proper
operation of the electricity supply around the country, sources
hoped. 
</P>
</TEXT>
