<HEADLINE> At Least 9 Killed, 170 Injured in Alberta Tornado Tragedy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- At least nine campers were killed
and 170 injured in the tornado tragedy in Canada's western
province of Alberta, Canadian media reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Police are still working to square the list of the injured
supplied by half a dozen hospitals in Pine Lake, where up to 100
rescue workers continue their search for survivors in the Green
Acre trailer park and camp ground.
</P>
<P>
There were 429 trailers and at least 400 campers at the
campsite when the powerful twister descended at the speed of 300
kilometers an hour.
</P>
<P>
"How many people were here? We really don't know," said police
officer Dan Doyle, indicating the casualties might be even higher.
</P>
<P>
"In all likelihood that may happen, especially when you take
into account the number of people who may have been out on the
lake at the time," he added.
</P>
<P>
Authorities are yet to confirm a report that several local
fishermen were caught out in the storm.
</P>
<P>
The rescue mission is being intensified with helicopters
equipped with infrared search technology put to use while about
150 troops from the provincial capital Edmonton get prepared to
head into the area.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien delivered a national
speech Saturday to express sadness and consolation "to all those
who lost family and loved ones, as well as to those who suffered
injuries or damages."
</P>
<P>
Alberta Premier Ralph Klein and Canadian Alliance leader
Stockwell Day made an inspection tour Friday of the area hit by
the tornado on Friday afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
