<HEADLINE> Britain Urges Sri Lanka's Tamil Parties to Support Consensus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 16 (Xinhua) -- A visiting senior British official
has urged the Tamil political parties in Sri Lanka to adopt
positive approach towards the consensus reached between the
government and the main Opposition on proposals to resolve the
ethnic conflict, the official Sunday Observer reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Peter Westamacott, deputy under secretary of state in the
Foreign and Commonwealth Office of Britain, was here during the
past two days to obtain a first hand situation of Sri Lanka's
political situation.
</P>
<P>
Westamacott, who had met the Tamil political parties in Colombo
Friday evening, told the newspaper that his country is "very
particular" that a political settlement should be found to the
ethnic problem in Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the consensus reached between the Sri Lankan
government and the main Opposition United National Party (UNP), he
suggested that whatever the shortcomings of the peace proposals by
the two major political parties in the country, the Tamil
political parties should take a "positive approach" towards the
proposals and sort out the issues that were not acceptable to the
Tamils.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the talks with the representatives of the Tamil
parties, he suggested that all efforts must be focused on reaching
a political settlement as early as possible to bring an end to the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
Westamacott, who left here Saturday morning, had meetings with
Minister of Foreign Affairs Lakshman Kadirgamar and the Leader of
the Opposition and the UNP Ranil Wickramasinghe during his brief
visit.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan government is talking with minority Tamil
parties in a bid to hammer out a consensus on constitutional
reform proposals which aim to end the 17-year ethnic conflicts
between government troops and Tamil rebels who have been fighting
a war for a separate Tamil state in the north and east of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The government and the UNP reached consensus on the
constitutional reform proposals last week after four months of
peace talks. The government would present the proposals before
Parliament in early next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
