<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Violence Continues in Ambon, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Gunfights continued in Ambon,
capital of Indonesia's Maluku province, on Saturday, forcing
residents to stay at home for fear of being shot.
</P>
<P>
"Sounds of gunfire and grenade and bomb explosions have been
heard since 07:00 a.m. (local time). It is like a war in the
Middle East or something. Thick smoke is billowing out here and
there. We cannot see anything farther than 20 meters," The Jakarta
Post Sunday quoted a reporter based in Ambon as saying.
</P>
<P>
The reporter said no one dared to go out, "therefore there is
no way for us to find out how many more people have been killed
and how many buildings were ravaged or burned down on Saturday."
</P>
<P>
But the Antara News Agency reported that four people were
killed by gunshots and six others injured in three different
places in Ambon, about 2,300 kilometers northeast of Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, two people aboard the speed boat "
Sampan Rua" en route from Passo port on Ambon island to Haria port
on the nearby Saparua island were also killed by gunshots in the
waters of Tanjung Tial on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The prolonged battle in Ambon has apparently affected the local
economy.
</P>
<P>
"There is a lack of kerosene and rice. A liter of kerosene
usually costs 600 rupiah (7 U.S. cents), but now we have to cover
a three-kilometer distance up the hill to get kerosene at 1,500
rupiah (18 cents) per liter. A kilogram of rice is now 4,000
rupiah (44 cents), or 1,000 rupiah more than the old price," a
local woman told the Jakarta Post.
</P>
<P>
Violence has been rife in Ambon since the enactment of the
civil emergency in Maluku and North Maluku provinces last month.
</P>
<P>
The spice islands of Maluku have been wrecked by communal
clashes since early 1999. Thousands of people were either killed
or wounded and hundreds of public buildings destroyed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
