<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 People's Daily
</P>
<P>
-- China's information industry maintained good development
momentum in the first half of this year, said Cheng Guanghui,
spokesman for the Ministry of Information Industry at a press
release held by the Information Office of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
The communications sector scored a business income of 123.4
billion yuan in January-May, up 27.1 percent from a year earlier.
Sales income from electronic information products totaled 200.7
billion yuan, an increase of 32.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- China's civil affairs and finance ministries provided 281
million yuan (33.86 million U.S. dollars) recently to aim local
people in areas stricken by natural disasters. Statistics show
that the departments under the State Council have already offered
more than one billion yuan (120 million U.S. dollars) of disaster
relief funds so far this year.
</P>
<P>
 Xinhua Daily Telegraph
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan and visiting Russian
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov Saturday discussed a range of issues
focusing on Sino-Russian relations, and called Russian President
Vladimir Putin's forthcoming visit to China a major event in
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Tang Jiaxuan said that President Putin's China visit will play
an important role in pushing forward the Sino-Russian strategic
partnership in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
China Daily
</P>
<P>
-- China plans to double its hydropower installed capacity
during the next 15 years, from 75 million kilowatts in 2000 to 150
million kilowatts by 2015.
</P>
<P>
The move will lay a sound foundation for the formation of a
nationwide grid and for transmitting more electricity from western
China to the east, said Zhou Dabing, vice-president of the State
Power Corporation of China, the nation's leading power producer.
</P>
<P>
-- Total foreign investment in Beijing in the first four months
was 160 million U.S. dollars, an 86 percent increase compared with
the same period last year, according to statistics provided by the
Beijing Customs. This indicates that Beijing's economy is doing
well, sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
