<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Education News in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Following is a review of the major
education news released by Xinhua from July 10 to July 15:
</P>
<P>
Chinese Enthusiastic at Computer Skill Examinations
</P>
<P>
Over 1.37 million Chinese passed the national computer skill
examinations and got certificates up to the end of June this year,
according to the Ministry of Education.
</P>
<P>
About 667,000 Chinese sit for the exam in the fist half of this
year, an increase of 22 percent from a year earlier, and 230,000
people, or 34.49 percent of the total, passed it.
</P>
<P>
Since the exam was initiated in 1994, a total of 3.42 million
Chinese have participated in the tests, statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Youth Urged to Work For Better Future
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of millions of Chinese youth were urged to redouble
their efforts to work for a better future for themselves and the
country.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao in a
message of congratulation to the national congresses of the All-
China Youth Federation and the All-China Students' Federation,
which opened Tuesday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,670 delegates will revise the constitutions and elect
new leading bodies of the organizations during the week-long
congresses.
</P>
<P>
China to Build 10 University-based High-tech Parks
</P>
<P>
Ten university-based high-tech parks will appear in China
within 10 years, according to the Ministry of Education.
</P>
<P>
In the coming decade, China's university high-tech parks should
become the most vigorous element of the country's technology
innovation system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000716.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Education News in China (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China to Speed Up Distance Education
</P>
<P>
China plans to build more information expressways to facilitate
its burgeoning distance education, and most municipalities and
provinces will open high-speed transmission portals by the end of
this year, according to the Education Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The China Education and Research Network has already linked
over 70 cities involving three million users in some 700
universities and science and research units.
</P>
<P>
China Gives Special Funding to Elite University Teachers
</P>
<P>
China will provide special funding to elite university teachers
across the country and a national program to this effect has been
launched recently.
</P>
<P>
An Education Ministry official said on July 12 that the program,
the first of this kind in China, is aimed at nurturing elite
middle-aged and young university teachers, and improving their
teaching skills and innovation ability.
</P>
<P>
In the first phase, 3,259 teachers in 332 universities and
colleges, 82.8 percent of them middle-aged and young teachers, are
each funded with 120,000 yuan for reach projects.
</P>
<P>
China Builds More Key Labs at Universities
</P>
<P>
China has made remarkable progress in construction of
university key labs. Nearly two thirds of the 150 state-level key
labs are located in universities. University key labs are
important bases for expanding high-level basic research and
nurturing experts, as well as centers for academic exchanges.
</P>
</TEXT>
