<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
major environment news stories Xinhua released from July 9 to July
15:
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang to Raise More Locust-Killing Fowl
</P>
<P>
Northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region has decided
to battle this year's onslaught of crop-eating locusts with the
big guns: chickens and ducks.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, over 700,000 of the train-to-eat-locust fowl
have been credited for killing a substantial proportion of the
insects that threatened farmland in one of the region's worst
plagues of the pest in years.
</P>
<P>
Pollution in Guangdong Decreasing
</P>
<P>
Officials announced Monday that heavy pollution in Guangdong
Province, south China, is decreasing, which is good news for
nearby Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The province's air pollution index has dropped by 0.3 points
compared with last year, and air quality in 14 cities has improved
remarkably, said Xu Deli, deputy governor of Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
Birds Find Paradise in Yellow River Delta
</P>
<P>
Birds have found a paradise in the reed marshes on the Yellow
River Delta.
</P>
<P>
The harmonious ecological environment came into being after the
government of Shandong Province at the lower reaches of the river
adopted the policy of turning farmland into marshes, more than two
decades after a massive land reclamation campaign.
</P>
<P>
Millions More Donated to Protect Yangtze River
</P>
<P>
More than 1.7 million yuan (about 200,000 U.S. dollars) in
donations has been raised by delegates attending the First Plenum
of the All-China Youth Federation's Ninth National Committee to
build a forest belt to protect the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The money will be used to build the China Youth Forest at the
middle reaches of the Yangtze River in Hubei Province at the
middle reaches of the river.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000716.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Youngsters' Environmental Protection Project Launched
</P>
<P>
A project calling for youngsters to participate in
environmental protection, sponsored by a dozen of Beijing-based
organizations, was officially launched Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
With the theme to uphold sustainable development and protect
the environment, the project calls for youngsters across the
country to understand the sustainable development strategy and
plant trees, in a bid to enhance public awareness about
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
China Affected by Global Warming: Scientist
</P>
<P>
The temperatures of the world will continue to rise in the next
30 years and China will be no exception, according to a leading
Chinese scientist here.
</P>
<P>
Over the past month, much of the world has been hit by waves of
heat. The Chinese capital of Beijing has already witnessed
temperatures above the major psychological mark of 40 degree
Centigrade.
</P>
<P>
China Closely Monitoring Red Tide
</P>
<P>
China's State Oceanic Administration has called on the coastal
areas to strengthen their round-the-clock monitoring against red
tide, which kills fish and other organisms in sea waters.
</P>
<P>
The urgent call was made with the approaching of the season of
red tide outbreak in offshore areas.
</P>
<P>
A number of large-scale red tides have been reported at the
Zhoushan Islands, east China's Zhejiang Province, since May, said
Li Hang, an official from the China Maritime Supervision Corps.
</P>
<P>
Wild Animals Increasing Rapidly in Tarim River Valley
</P>
<P>
The number of wild animals has grown rapidly in the Tarim River
valley, northwest China, over the past 20 years due to improved
environment, said an engineer who has been engaged in wild animal
protection for decades.
</P>
<P>
Gu Zhengqin said that surveys in recent years indicate that the
number of wild animals can match that of the domestic animals,
mainly horses, cattle and sheep, in some places in the river
valley. 
</P>
</TEXT>
