<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Use Expropriation in Land Reform: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The South African government
would use expropriation as a tool for land reform where necessary,
said Agriculture Minister Thoko Didiza in Port Elizabeth on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing reporters at the end of the African National
Congress' national general council, the minister said
expropriation is nothing new and was provided for in terms of the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
While expropriation is not the only option to meet the demands
of land hungry South Africans, the Expropriation Act will be used
where necessary, she said.
</P>
<P>
The Act was in fact used only two weeks ago, Didiza said,
without giving more details.
</P>
<P>
She said the real issue revolves around compensation and
whether the state would have to pay market related prices.
</P>
<P>
Delegates attending the council meeting earlier this week
debated the issue in their commissions.
</P>
<P>
According to a draft report tabled before the council on
Saturday, the delegates agreed that land reform should be speeded
up through expropriation and redistribution of under-utilized and
unused farmland, including state owned land.
</P>
<P>
"The land reform program must be accelerated to give rural poor
more equitable access to productive land and correct the highly
skewed ownership land patterns," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The delegates also called on the party's highest decision-
making body in between national conferences, the National
Executive Committee, to convene a national workshop to assess both
land restitution and reform.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, ANC presidency head Smuts Ngonyama said the
delegates, especially those from the rural areas, were generally
satisfied with the pace of land reform.
</P>
<P>
However, there was a feeling that the "willing seller, willing
buyer" method might prove too costly for the state, he said.
</P>
<P>
He was echoed by Agri South Africa chief executive officer Jack
Raath, who was quoted by the South African Press Association as
saying that in terms of commercial land, there is no reason to opt
for the expropriation route.
</P>
<P>
"You don't need it. There is enough land and prices are going
down if you look at agricultural land. You can get it on the
market, you don't need expropriation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Any attempt to expropriate under these circumstances would put
it mildly stuff up the whole land market and the capital base of
agriculture, he said.
</P>
<P>
"However, organized agriculture held a different view if
expropriation was to be used as 'an important instrument in
finalizing the restitution process'," Raath said.
</P>
<P>
"If the process is taking too long and is going to slow and
there are obstacles, then there is no problem if people proceed
with expropriation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Expropriation should never become the government's first choice
in normal land transactions, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
However, the National Land Committee (NLC) agreed with the view
of ANC delegates that the "willing seller, willing buyer" approach
would be financially crippling.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, quality land is not being redistributed through this
method, said NLC deputy director Tom Lebert.
</P>
<P>
"What tends to come on the market is fairly marginal. The
arable resources are quite small," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Lebert, the issue is not whether land should be
expropriated, but that of compensation.
</P>
<P>
The Constitution's property clause did not only refer to market
value, but provided for several other factors to determine "just
and equitable" compensation, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
