<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Oil Pipeline Fire Death Toll Rises to 100 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The death toll of the oil pipeline
fire in Nigeria's eastern Delta State has risen to 100 on Monday,
according to local media reports.
</P>
<P>
Local government officials were quoted as saying that the
casualty figure was increasing as more bodies were found from the
nearby rivers.
</P>
<P>
The renewed fire broke out on Sunday when vandals scooped up
gushing gasoline near a refinery in the oil-producing town of
Warri a few days after an earlier pipeline explosion at a nearby
village which claimed more than 250 lives.
</P>
<P>
A local police officer said that Sunday's pipeline explosion
was caused when one of the villagers siphoning gasoline from the
pipeline lit a cigarette.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government has been fighting for the control of
pipeline vandalism which often results in pipeline explosion in
the oil-producing states. Local villagers living close to
pipelines have ignored similar disasters and repeated to cash in
on a thriving black market for refined products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
