<DOCNO> XIE20000716.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian President Calls for Total Debt Cancellation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick Chiluba
Monday called for the total cancellation of foreign debts the
African countries and his country in particular owe, warning that
"unless this is done all our efforts and resources will be
dissipated in unsustainable debt repayments and deprivation."
</P>
<P>
Chiluba made the appeal at the three-day 12th Consultative
Group (CG) meeting attended by representatives from the World Bank,
the International Monetary Fund, the European Union and a number
of donor countries.
</P>
<P>
"In order to consolidate the gains we have made, and will make
from economic growth strategies, the heavy indebtedness, which is
a yoke on our efforts, needs to be addressed," he told the meeting,
which is to review and assess the country's short and long-term
economic agenda and solicit development assistance to Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The president said that whereas the current mechanisms for debt
relief are welcome, they do not go far enough in tackling Africa's
debt burden.
</P>
<P>
On his country's economic reform, the president said that since
1991, when he took power, Zambia has undertaken perhaps the most
comprehensive economic and structural reforms in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Beyond all precedent in the region, we have decontrolled
prices and interest rates, removed all subsidies, removed exchange
controls and all restrictions on imports and exports and lowered
tariffs significantly," he said, adding that these measures have
brought about many changes.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said his country's resolve remains unwavering to
achieve and maintain macro-economic stability throughout prudent
budget management, improved tax administration and expenditure
controls.
</P>
<P>
On the privatization of his country's copper mines, he said
that Zambia's economic performance has been dependent on the
fortunes of its mining industry, the Zambia Consolidated Copper
Mines (ZCCM) in particular.
</P>
<P>
With the conclusion of the privatization of ZCCM in March this
year the restoration of confidence in the economy and the
resumption of new investment is expected in the mining industry,
he said.
</P>
<P>
On the country's agriculture, Chiluba said that with an arable
land area of 42 million hectares and abundant water resources,
Zambia is agreeably one of the region's sleeping giants as far as
agricultural production is concerned.
</P>
<P>
Zambia can turn this sector into a veritable driving engine for
growth in the economy and reducing poverty over the next few years,
he assured, noting that presently agriculture provides a
livelihood for over 50 percent of Zambians but only generates
about 18 percent of its gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
Zambian government ministers and representatives of civil
societies are also attending the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
