<HEADLINE> S. Asian Journalists Conduct AIDS Study in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- A group of journalists from South
Asia is now in Uganda for a one-week study of the HIV/AIDS
situation in the east African country and the policy the country
has been using to fight the disease, Radio Uganda reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The journalists hailed the government's policy of openness in
fighting the major killer disease in the country, saying that
Uganda has so far achieved a great success in this regard.
</P>
<P>
It said that the journalists will visit various organizations
that are fighting the disease in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has brought down the prevalence of HIV/AIDS infection
country-wide from over 30 percent in the 1980s and early 1990s to
the current 10 percent, thanks to the pains-efforts of the
government and enhanced awareness of the population. 
</P>
