<HEADLINE> One Indian U.N. Peacekeeper Killed in S. Leone  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 17 (Xinhua) -- An Indian peacekeeper was killed and
seven others wounded in a weekend operation to rescue a trapped
Indian battalion and a group of military observers, reports
reaching here from Freetown quoted a U.N. official as saying on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"This is the price we paid for the freedom of our brothers and
sisters in Sierra Leone," U.N. force commander Major General Vijay
Jetley said.
</P>
<P>
The dead soldier was a member of the rescue commando, which on
Saturday ventured into the eastern town of Kailahun to walk out
the 222 Indian soldiers and 11 international military observers,
who had been surrounded in their camp by the rebels since early in
May.
</P>
<P>
The casualty was caused in an exchange of fire with the rebels,
on the combined party's exodus to the U.N. controlled town of Daru.
</P>
</TEXT>
