<HEADLINE> Uganda's Exports Drop Sharply in Last Fiscal Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's exports fell by 15
percent in the 1999-2000 fiscal year ending this June, New Vision
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The fall was mainly caused by the decline of coffee prices on
the world markets, which cost Uganda more than 100 million U.S.
dollars in the fiscal year, according to the Quarterly Report
produced by the Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
The ban imposed by the European Union on Uganda's fish exports
also reduced the country's earnings by more than 30 million
dollars, says the report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Uganda's exports to Britain dropped from 670 million
dollars in 1997 to 450 million dollars in 1999.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the high cargo transportation cost was to
blame for the fall of Uganda's exports to Britain, because Uganda
is landlocked and its exporting products have to be flown out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
