<HEADLINE> Construction Crew Sets Off Small Fire in White House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"There was a small fire in the East Wing of the White House
during construction work. Some floor boards burned," spokeswoman
Nanda Chitre said in Camp David, Maryland State, where President
Bill Clinton is holding Middle East peace talks with Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
Three fire trucks responded, Chitre said. The fire did not
spread and was quickly extinguished. There was no estimate of
damage, but workers were able to resume work almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
The White House's East Wing contains First Lady Hillary Clinton
's offices while the president's famed Oval Office and the offices
of his top aides are located in the West Wing.
</P>
<P>
The 200-year-old building has withstood two major fires. Much
of the interior of the building was burned by the British in 1814.
In 1929, while Herbert Hoover was president, a fire damaged the
West Wing, which holds the Oval Office and the business offices of
the presidency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
