<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Director Urges Zambia to Further Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- World Bank Director Michael Sarris
Monday urged Zambia to speed up its economic development, warning
that failure to make more progress would jeopardize previous gains
and seriously compromise future growth and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Sarris made the call at the three-day 12th Consultative Group (
CG) meeting beginning here Sunday, which is attended by
representatives from the World Bank, the International Monetary
Fund and some donor nations as well.
</P>
<P>
To develop its economy, Sarris said Zambia needs to remove the
remaining obstacles to a diversified economy, adding that in this
regard impediments to private business development should be
cleared and more competition be introduced into the financial
sector.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the importance to develop the country's
agricultural sector, which employs 70 percent of its workforce and
contributes more than half of its exports in 1999.
</P>
<P>
To this end, the country needs to improve physical and social
infrastructure in the rural economy, further liberalize
agricultural markets and provide essential inputs on a more
competitive basis, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sarris also pressed Zambia to curb corruption in the
country.
</P>
<P>
"Low civil service pay and morale, bureaucratic red tape,
onerous regulations, and weak enforcement mechanisms are breeding
ground for corruption, which could erode investor confidence,
limit economic growth and redirect government spending away from
poverty reduction," Sarris said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is convened to review and assess Zambia's short and
long-term economic agenda and to solicit development assistance
for the country.
</P>
<P>
Zambian government ministers and representatives of civil
societies are also present at the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
