<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> About Half of Nigerian Children Stunted: UNICEF Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 17 (Xinhua) -- More than 43 percent of Nigerian
children under the age of five suffer stunted growth due to
inadequate feeding and repeated illness, said a report released by
the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report, entitled "Progress on Nations 2000", listed Nigeria
as the sixth nation in sub-Saharan African with the highest number
of children suffering from stunted growth while Ethiopia topped
the list with 64 percent.
</P>
<P>
Inadequate feeding and repeated illness are the immediate
causes of stunting among young children, said the report, adding
that the vicious cycle was a result of poverty and the consequent
inability of families to adequately cater for their children.
</P>
<P>
Deprivations in feeding and care that impair growth in the
critical first years may also reduce a child's cognitive
development and learning ability, often leading to poor school
performance and drop out, it said.
</P>
<P>
The report also indicated that 39 percent, about 209 million
children under five in the developing world, are stunted, with
Asia and sub-Saharan Africa recording the highest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
